This isn't a valid promise-like object either, doing `await` on that will never resolve.

So a full check could be something like this:

```ts
// Quick-check for normal Promises
if (result instanceof Promise || typeof result === "object" && result !== null && typeof result.then === "function" && result.then.length >= 1) {
  // ...
}
```

One could also consider doing some sort of a test-by-fire on a potential promise-like:

```ts
async function testPromiseLike(maybePromiseLike: unknown, bench) {
  if (typeof maybePromiseLike !== "object" || maybePromiseLike === null) {
    return false;
  } else if (typeof maybePromiseLike.then !== "function" || maybePromiseLike.then.length === 0) {
    return false;
  }
  // Looks like a promise, now lets see if it walks like a promise
  return await Promise.race([
    maybePromiseLike.then(() => true, () => true), // Return or throw, it doesn't matter
    new Promise((res) => setTimeout(() => res(false), bench.timeout)), // Does not resolve within the bench timeout, this does not seem like a real promise
  ]);
}
```

Now if the return value looks and walks like a Promise, it'll get used like a promise. Otherwise it'll be treated as a sync function.

