Ah, this has to do with the sick example I showed in Discord that used a signal handler on the FFI Rust side to call the registered callback.

So a code like this:
```js
let shouldContinueLoop = true;
const callback = () => {
  console.log("Stop looping!");
  shouldContinueLoop = false;
};
const regCb = new Deno.RegisteredCallback({ parameters: [], result: "void" }, callback);
dylib.symbols.store_callback(regCb);
dylib.symbols.call_stored_callback_after_delay(); // Sets up a SIGALRM interrupt handler that calls the stored callback, and then sets up a SIGALRM interrupt signal to be fired in 2 seconds time.

let count = 0;
while(shouldContinueLoop) {
  if (count++ == 10 ** 6) {
  console.log("No I won't!");
 }
}
```
will output:
> Stop looping!
> No I won't!
and will never exit.

If you add a `performance.now()` call into the loop, then it will exit properly.
If you add a `Math.random()` call into the loop, then it will panic.
Also, if you add a `console.trace()` to the callback you'll see the callback emanating from inside the while-loop.
So, if an interrupt handler is setup to call back into JS and Deno currently has an active stack, the callback will simply step on top of that stack and do its work. That does not mean that the data that Deno (or V8, rather) uses will be affected as expected.

This is, I think, something that should be carefully documented but trying to fight against this would probably not be a good idea, as I don't think that at present we have the tools to do anything except accept this.

